ce:section.ce:para:
As an industrial by-product, SP is a derivative of petroleum pitch. Its principal part is polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons and edge defects are aliphatic hydrocarbons and oxygen-containing groups [14,28,29]. Namely, hydrophobicity and hydrophilicity coexist in SP. The oxygen-containing groups in SP are mainly composed of –COOH, anhydride, lactone, –OH, –SO3H, –CO and quinone (Fig. S2). These groups make SP adequately dispersible in alkaline solution in highly disordered state. Because of the ultrafine planar aromatic size L
                        a of 3.2 nm and crystal size L
                        c of 1.87 nm (Fig. S1 and Table 2

                        ), SP can also be considered as graphene quantum dots (GQDs) [14,30,31]. As is well-known, triblock copolymer P123 can serve as a structure-directing agent by forming ample lamellar micelles. Arising therefrom, the physical/chemical force field of these disorganized GQDs in aqueous can be altered by forming firm hydrogen-bonding networks between lamellar micelles and GQDs, resulting in the ordered state of GQDs. As a consequence, stable lamellar lyotropic liquid crystals can come into being by the interface self-assembly [14,30,32]. During the temperature-rise period, the P123 molecules all decompose. Meanwhile, the aliphatic hydrocarbon defects of GQDs can generate vast free radicals (CH2·), accompanying with the formation of C–C covalent bonds between adjacent carbonaceous microcrystallines [33]. With the further increase of temperature, the rearrangement of carbon skeleton is expected through the aromatization of carbon materials [33–35]. After KOH activation and high-temperature annealing, the 2D PCN with miscellaneous pores is synthesized successfully (shown in Scheme 1
                        ).

The N2 adsorption-desorption isotherm of PCN1-800 (Fig. 4
                        a) exhibits a typical I curve, suggesting the prevailing microporous peculiarity (Table 3
                        ). The sharp rise of N2-adsorption at infinitesimal relative pressure uncovers the vast micropores, while the unobvious hysteresis loop discloses small quantities of mesopores [8,45]. The PSD curve (Fig. 4b) further gives a bright outlook towards the pore structure of PCN1-800. It can be seen that the pores of PCN1-800 are chiefly situated in 0.54 nm, 0.8 nm, 1.17 nm, 1.58 nm and 2.2 nm. Fortunately, there are extremely low-content of pores larger than 6 nm, confirmed by the almost no increases of cumulative pore volume and surface area with the pore size larger than 6 nm (inset of Fig. 4b and Fig. S3). This is of great importance for the high packing density and carbon yield of PCN1-800.
